The course covers the key political, economic and security issues of the EU-Russia relations against a broad empirical background of official documents and wider public debates. It discusses the actors' identities, history of EU-Russia relations since the collapse of the Soviet Union, institutional frameworks, bilateral as well as multilateral, issues of path-dependence in the lead-up to the 2014 crisis and the main items on the current agenda. The latter include the sanctions, security, memory, trade and energy, and people-to-people contacts. During the seminar sessions, the discussion is organised around contemporary sources representing the controversies that defined the parties' standing and the political outcomes.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course provides an overview of the agenda of EU-Russia relations, reviews their history, institutional foundations analyses the key factors shaping the patterns of both high-profile conflict and low-key cooperation.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completing the course, the students will be able to: 1)	understand the key problems defining the agenda of the relations between the EU and Russia; 2)	relate specific issues of EU-Russia relations to main ideological and theoretical paradigms and be able to critically re-assess the origins and background of specific political discourses; 3)	use most important sources of information and documents in the field of EU-Russia relations; 4)	be able to use this knowledge by participating in an informed and constructive debate on all aspects of EU-Russia relations.
